<div class="row-fluid">
    <div class="span12">
        <h2>Cite This Dataset</h2>
    </div>
</div>    
<div class="row-fluid">
    <div class="span8">
        
        <div class="well">
            <a href="/embed?url=<%=params[:url]%>&style=citation/default" class="embed">Use</a>
            <%= partial( :"citation/default" ) %>            
        </div>                                
        <% if @attribution_data[:issued] && @attribution_data[:modified] %>
            <div class="well">
                <a href="/embed?url=<%=params[:url]%>&style=citation/issued_and_modified" class="embed">Use</a>
                <%= partial( :"citation/issued_and_modified" ) %>
            </div>                
        <% end %>                    
        <div class="well">
            <a href="/embed?url=<%=params[:url]%>&style=citation/issued_and_retrieved" class="embed">Use</a>
            <%= partial( :"citation/issued_and_retrieved" ) %>            
        </div>            
                
    </div>
    <div class="span4">
        <p>Citations are typically more formal ways to link to a data source. While attribution statements are usually used to 
        acknowledge the efforts of a data publisher, a citation is usually intended to help a user understand which dataset (and version of that 
        dataset) was used in an application or analysis. E.g. to allow a user to recreate the analysis.</p>
        <p>
        Even if you plan to include a formal citation of a dataset, you may also need to include an attribution statement as well.
        </p>
    </div>
</div>
